<subSubSection pageId="192" pageNumber="193" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="192.[151,1436,151,500]" pageId="192" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,368,392]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="192" pageNumber="193" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This is the best-known intertidal hermit crab of 
<collectingRegion box="[885,998,367,391]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="192" pageNumber="193">California</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1059,1147,367,391]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="192" pageNumber="193">Oregon</collectingRegion>
. It is abundant along the outer coastline and just inside the mouths of larger bays and harbors, such as San Francisco Bay and Los 
<collectingRegion box="[1344,1436,404,428]" country="Philippines" name="Angeles" pageId="192" pageNumber="193">Angeles</collectingRegion>
Harbor. It usually inhabits shells of 
<taxonomicName box="[561,691,440,464]" class="Gastropoda" family="Tegulidae" genus="Tegula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="192" pageNumber="193" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[561,636,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="192" pageNumber="193">Tegula</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
Slipper shells (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1809" box="[869,1028,439,463]" class="Gastropoda" family="Calyptraeidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="192" pageNumber="193" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Calyptraeidae</taxonomicName>
) may live inside the aperture of the shell or on top of it.
</paragraph>
